<style type="text/css">

.tocify {
width: 20%;
max-height: 90%;
overflow: auto;
margin-left: 2%;
position: fixed;
border: 1px solid #ccc;
border-radius: 6px;
}

.tocify ul, .tocify li {
list-style: none;
margin: 0;
padding: 0;
border: none;
line-height: 30px;
}

.tocify-header {
text-indent: 10px;
}

.tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 20px;
display: none;
}

.tocify-subheader li {
font-size: 12px;
}

.tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 30px;
}
.tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 40px;
}
.tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 50px;
}
.tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 60px;
}

.tocify .tocify-item > a, .tocify .nav-list .nav-header {
margin: 0px;
}

.tocify .tocify-item a, .tocify .list-group-item {
padding: 5px;
}
.tocify .nav-pills > li {
float: none;
}


</style>

<script>

/**
 * jQuery Plugin: Sticky Tabs
 *
 * @author Aidan Lister <aidan@php.net>
 * adapted by Ruben Arslan to activate parent tabs too
 * http://www.aidanlister.com/2014/03/persisting-the-tab-state-in-bootstrap/
 */
(function($) {
  "use strict";
  $.fn.rmarkdownStickyTabs = function() {
    var context = this;
    // Show the tab corresponding with the hash in the URL, or the first tab
    var showStuffFromHash = function() {
      var hash = window.location.hash;
      var selector = hash ? 'a[href="' + hash + '"]' : 'li.active > a';
      var $selector = $(selector, context);
      if($selector.data('toggle') === "tab") {
        $selector.tab('show');
        // walk up the ancestors of this element, show any hidden tabs
        $selector.parents('.section.tabset').each(function(i, elm) {
          var link = $('a[href="#' + $(elm).attr('id') + '"]');
          if(link.data('toggle') === "tab") {
            link.tab("show");
          }
        });
      }
    };


    // Set the correct tab when the page loads
    showStuffFromHash(context);

    // Set the correct tab when a user uses their back/forward button
    $(window).on('hashchange', function() {
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    // Change the URL when tabs are clicked
    $('a', context).on('click', function(e) {
      history.pushState(null, null, this.href);
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    return this;
  };
}(jQuery));

window.buildTabsets = function(tocID) {

  // build a tabset from a section div with the .tabset class
  function buildTabset(tabset) {

    // check for fade and pills options
    var fade = tabset.hasClass("tabset-fade");
    var pills = tabset.hasClass("tabset-pills");
    var navClass = pills ? "nav-pills" : "nav-tabs";

    // determine the heading level of the tabset and tabs
    var match = tabset.attr('class').match(/level(\d) /);
    if (match === null)
      return;
    var tabsetLevel = Number(match[1]);
    var tabLevel = tabsetLevel + 1;

    // find all subheadings immediately below
    var tabs = tabset.find("div.section.level" + tabLevel);
    if (!tabs.length)
      return;

    // create tablist and tab-content elements
    var tabList = $('<ul class="nav ' + navClass + '" role="tablist"></ul>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabList);
    var tabContent = $('<div class="tab-content"></div>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabContent);

    // build the tabset
    var activeTab = 0;
    tabs.each(function(i) {

      // get the tab div
      var tab = $(tabs[i]);

      // get the id then sanitize it for use with bootstrap tabs
      var id = tab.attr('id');

      // see if this is marked as the active tab
      if (tab.hasClass('active'))
        activeTab = i;

      // remove any table of contents entries associated with
      // this ID (since we'll be removing the heading element)
      $("div#" + tocID + " li a[href='#" + id + "']").parent().remove();

      // sanitize the id for use with bootstrap tabs
      id = id.replace(/[.\/?&!#<>]/g, '').replace(/\s/g, '_');
      tab.attr('id', id);

      // get the heading element within it, grab it's text, then remove it
      var heading = tab.find('h' + tabLevel + ':first');
      var headingText = heading.html();
      heading.remove();

      // build and append the tab list item
      var a = $('<a role="tab" data-toggle="tab">' + headingText + '</a>');
      a.attr('href', '#' + id);
      a.attr('aria-controls', id);
      var li = $('<li role="presentation"></li>');
      li.append(a);
      tabList.append(li);

      // set it's attributes
      tab.attr('role', 'tabpanel');
      tab.addClass('tab-pane');
      tab.addClass('tabbed-pane');
      if (fade)
        tab.addClass('fade');

      // move it into the tab content div
      tab.detach().appendTo(tabContent);
    });

    // set active tab
    $(tabList.children('li')[activeTab]).addClass('active');
    var active = $(tabContent.children('div.section')[activeTab]);
    active.addClass('active');
    if (fade)
      active.addClass('in');

    if (tabset.hasClass("tabset-sticky"))
      tabset.rmarkdownStickyTabs();
  }

  // convert section divs with the .tabset class to tabsets
  var tabsets = $("div.section.tabset");
  tabsets.each(function(i) {
    buildTabset($(tabsets[i]));
  });
};

</script>

<div id="header">



<h1 class="title toc-ignore">Leveraging Data Insights to Drive Digital
Marketing Strategy</h1>
<h3 class="subtitle">Data Analysis Case Study for Bellabeat Using R</h3>
<h4 class="author">Sahaf Shoshani</h4>
<h4 class="date">04/02/2023</h4>

</div>


<p>HTML and RMD files can be found on <a href="https://github.com/SahafShoshani/BellaBeat-Case-Study">Github</a></p>
<div id="bellabeat-introduction" class="section level2">
<h2>Bellabeat Introduction</h2>
<p>Bellabeat is a womens wellness brand that offers a comprehensive
range of products and services designed to enhance womens health. The
company specializes in creating wearables and complementary products
that track biometric and lifestyle data, enabling women to gain a deeper
understanding of their bodies and make informed decisions about their
health. By gathering data on activity, sleep, stress, and reproductive
health, Bellabeat empowers women with the knowledge they need to improve
their overall well-being and lifestyle habits.</p>
<p>Bellabeat products:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Bellabeat app: The Bellabeat app provides users with health data
related to their activity, sleep, stress, menstrual cycle, and
mindfulness habits. This data can help users better understand their
current habits and make healthy decisions. The Bellabeat app connects to
their line of smart wellness products.</p></li>
<li><p>Leaf: Bellabeats classic wellness tracker can be worn as a
bracelet, necklace, or clip. The Leaf tracker connects to the Bellabeat
app to track activity, sleep, and stress.</p></li>
<li><p>Time: This wellness watch combines the timeless look of a classic
timepiece with smart technology to track user activity, sleep, and
stress. The Time watch connects to the Bellabeat app to provide you with
insights into your daily wellness.</p></li>
<li><p>Spring: This is a water bottle that tracks daily water intake
using smart technology to ensure that you are appropriately hydrated
throughout the day. The Spring bottle connects to the Bellabeat app to
track your hydration levels.</p></li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="analysis-goal-and-overview" class="section level2">
<h2>Analysis Goal and Overview</h2>
<p>Gain insights for Bellabeat smart products from trends of
non-Bellabeat smart-devices consumers in order to reveal growth
opportunities for the company digital marketing strategy.<br></p>
<p>In this analysis, we explore approaches to effectively engage
potential consumers of smart devices and identify trends and patterns
related to their behaviors. Our analysis will cover various aspects of
user activity, including sleep patterns, health-related metrics such as
calorie and step counts, as well as intensity levels, heart rates, and
MET (metabolic equivalent of task) measurements.<br> Key stakeholders in
this analysis include Bellabeats co-founder and Chief Creative Officer
Urka Sren, as well as the Bellabeat executive and marketing analytics
teams.<br> For our analysis we will use the <a href="https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arashnic/fitbit">FitBit Fitness
Tracker Data</a>.</p>
</div>
<div id="prepare" class="section level2">
<h2>Prepare</h2>
<p><strong>Where is your data stored?</strong> <br> The data is can be
found online on Kaggle platform, and for this project was downloaded and
used locally.<br> <strong>How is the data organized?</strong> <br> The
data has 18 data sets, wide and long formats.<br> Datasets contains
information on activity, sleep, calories, intensities, steps, MET
scores, heart-rate and weight.<br> <strong>Are there issues with bias or
credibility in this data?</strong><br> The dataset is generated by
respondent to a distributed survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk between
12.02.2016-12.03.2016<br> 33 eligible Fitbit users consented to the
submission of personal tracker data and become a part of the
dataset.<br></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Reliable</strong>  The data seems to be collected from a
random sample of the survey respondents, But there is no explanation
about this procedure, and no details about the survey itself. We do not
know for sure that this dataset is unbiased. Further more, there is no
documentation about reliability check from FitBit or any reference about
the cleaning process.</li>
<li><strong>Original</strong>  The data is a third party source, and
the original files cant be traced online. Second party source is Zenodo
website and the data originally arranged in to separate files for each
day (12.4.16-12.5.16). The data is indexed in OpenAIRE. Datasets on
Kaggle are a merged version of the all the datasets. After checking we
can approve the merging has done correctly without the loss of
information.</li>
<li><strong>Comprehensive</strong>  The data is part comprehensive for
our analysis purposes. Some of the datasets contain just 8 users and 67
total rows which make it hard for analysis (weight dataset).</li>
<li><strong>Current</strong>  Data is from 2016, and might be less
useful for insights about current trends.</li>
<li><strong>Cited</strong>  The data is cited. Original Data lies in <a href="https://zenodo.org/record/53894#.ZCVAaXZBy3C">Zenodo
website</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Addressing licensing, privacy, security, and
accessibility</strong> <br> Data sets not showing any private details
about users, and can be used by the public for analysis uses.</p>
<p><strong>How does the data can help you achieving your goal? </strong>
<br> Our goal is to identify meaningful patterns and insights from the
data to inform our marketing strategy.<br> We plan to explore
relationships between different measures and visualize the data at
various time intervals, such as minute, hour, and week. Additionally, we
will analyze the distribution of different values to gain further
insights. All of these approaches will help us achieve our marketing
objectives.<br> <strong>Are there any problems with the
data?</strong><br> Kaggle article do mention that there is some
variation between output represents use of different types of Fitbit
trackers and individual tracking behaviors / preferences. To address the
issue, we will perform data cleaning and normalization
techniques.Additionally, we will perform statistical analysis to
identify and adjust for any biases or inconsistencies in the data.<br>
Additionally, there is no information provided on how the different
levels of the data were determined or defined. For that we would conduct
exploratory data analysis (EDA) on the data to see if there are any
patterns or inconsistencies that might indicate how the levels were
determined. This will involve examining the distributions of the data,
looking for outliers, and examining relationships between different
variables.</p>

<div id="activity" class="section level3">
<h3>Activity</h3>
<p>Datasets in use:</p>
<ul>
<li>dailyActivity</li>
<li>sleepDay (in order to better understand how reliable the data
is)</li>
</ul>
<div id="data-cleaning-and-reliability-analysis" class="section level4">
<h4>Data Cleaning and Reliability Analysis</h4>
<p>Upon examining the dailyActivity table, it becomes apparent that
numerous rows contain 0 values across all variables except for sedentary
minutes and calories burned. In order to derive meaningful insights
regarding activity patterns throughout the day, it is necessary to clean
this data.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>head(filter(dailyActivity, TotalSteps == 0)) # Incomplete data</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 6  16
##       Id Activ Total Total Track Logge VeryA Moder Light Seden
##    &lt;dbl&gt; &lt;chr&gt;     &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1 1.50e9 5/12/2       0       0       0       0       0       0       0       0
## 2 1.84e9 4/24/2       0       0       0       0       0       0       0       0
## 3 1.84e9 4/25/2       0       0       0       0       0       0       0       0
## 4 1.84e9 4/26/2       0       0       0       0       0       0       0       0
## 5 1.84e9 5/2/20       0       0       0       0       0       0       0       0
## 6 1.84e9 5/7/20       0       0       0       0       0       0       0       0
## #  with 6 more variables: VeryActiveMinutes &lt;dbl&gt;, FairlyActiveMinutes &lt;dbl&gt;,
## #   LightlyActiveMinutes &lt;dbl&gt;, SedentaryMinutes &lt;dbl&gt;, Calories &lt;dbl&gt;,
## #   ActivityDate_new &lt;date&gt;, and abbreviated variable names ActivityDate,
## #   TotalSteps, TotalDistance, TrackerDistance, LoggedActivitiesDistance,
## #   VeryActiveDistance, ModeratelyActiveDistance, LightActiveDistance,
## #   SedentaryActiveDistance</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>dailyActivity &lt;- dailyActivity %&gt;% filter(TotalSteps &gt; 0)</code></pre>
<p>There are four different levels of activity: Very active, Fairly
active, Lightly active, and Sedentary active. To evaluate the
reliability of these activity levels, we will investigate the
relationship between time and distance. A linear relationship should
exist, with the greatest slope observed for the very active level and
the least for the sedentary level.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>distance_long &lt;- dailyActivity %&gt;% 
  select(id = Id, date = ActivityDate_new, very_active = VeryActiveDistance, fairly_active = ModeratelyActiveDistance,
         lightly_active = LightActiveDistance, sedentary_active = SedentaryActiveDistance) %&gt;%
  pivot_longer(cols = very_active:sedentary_active,
               names_to = &quot;activity_type&quot;, values_to = &quot;average_distance&quot;)

minutes_long &lt;- dailyActivity %&gt;% 
  select(id = Id, date = ActivityDate_new, very_active = VeryActiveMinutes, fairly_active=FairlyActiveMinutes, 
         lightly_active = LightlyActiveMinutes, sedentary_active = SedentaryMinutes) %&gt;%
  pivot_longer(cols = very_active:sedentary_active,
               names_to = &quot;activity_type&quot;, values_to = &quot;average_time&quot;)

activityDistanceTime &lt;- inner_join(distance_long,minutes_long, by = c(&quot;date&quot;,&quot;id&quot;,&quot;activity_type&quot;))

activityDistanceTime %&gt;% ggplot(aes(x= average_time, y = average_distance)) + 
  geom_point()  + geom_smooth(method = &quot;lm&quot;) + facet_wrap(~activity_type) +
  labs(title = &quot;Activity Distance by Minutes&quot;, x = &quot;Minutes&quot;, y = &quot;Distance&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>As expected, we have observed differences in the slope values, with
the very active level having the greatest slope.</p>
<p>To further evaluate the dailyActivity dataset, we will verify that
the sum of all activity minutes equals the total number of minutes in a
day minus 1440. To achieve this, we will need to merge the data from the
sleepDay dataset to obtain the time spent in bed for each day.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>dailyActivity &lt;- dailyActivity %&gt;% mutate(sleep_mins = 1440-VeryActiveMinutes-FairlyActiveMinutes-
                                            LightlyActiveMinutes-SedentaryMinutes)

testTotalMinutes &lt;- inner_join(dailyActivity,sleepDay,by = c(&quot;Id&quot;,&quot;ActivityDate_new&quot; = &quot;SleepDay_new&quot;), multiple = &quot;all&quot;)
testTotalMinutes &lt;- testTotalMinutes %&gt;% filter(sleep_mins == TotalTimeInBed)
nrow(testTotalMinutes)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 126</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="activity-analysis" class="section level4">
<h4>Activity Analysis</h4>
<p>We observed that only 126 out of 413 rows accurately represent the
total minutes in a day. <br> The issue is that sedentary time includes
time spent in bed. Despite this issue, after verifying that our data
includes a diverse group of users, we can proceed to examine the
distribution of daily activity. We will select the necessary data and
transform it into a long format to create a new data table for
analysis.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>testActivity &lt;- testTotalMinutes %&gt;% 
  summarise(avg_very_active = mean(VeryActiveMinutes),
            avg_fairly_active = mean(FairlyActiveMinutes),
            avg_lightly_active = mean(LightlyActiveMinutes),
            avg_sedentary = mean(SedentaryMinutes)) %&gt;% 
  pivot_longer(cols = avg_very_active:avg_sedentary,
               names_to = &quot;activity_type&quot;, values_to = &quot;average_minutes&quot;)

summed_activity &lt;- testActivity %&gt;% group_by(activity_type) %&gt;%
  summarise(average_minutes = mean(average_minutes)) %&gt;% 
              summarise(activity_type,average_minutes,average_minutes_percent = average_minutes/sum(average_minutes)) %&gt;% 
  arrange(activity_type)

my_colors &lt;- c(&quot;#1C0C5B&quot;, &quot;#3D2C8D&quot;, &quot;#916BBF&quot;, &quot;#C996CC&quot;)
my_labels &lt;- c(&quot;Fairly Active&quot;,&quot;Lightly Active&quot;,&quot;Sedendary&quot;,&quot;Very Active&quot;)

summed_activity %&gt;% 
  mutate(avg_hours = format(as.POSIXct(average_minutes_percent*24*3600*(sum(average_minutes)/1440),
                                       origin = &quot;1970-01-01&quot;, tz = &quot;UTC&quot;),&quot;%H:%M&quot;)) %&gt;% 
  ggplot() + geom_col(aes(x = &quot;&quot;, y = average_minutes_percent, fill = my_colors), width = 1) +
  coord_polar(&quot;y&quot;, start = 0) + theme_void() +
  geom_text_repel(aes(x = 1.8, y = average_minutes_percent, color = my_colors,
                      label = paste0(scales::percent(average_minutes_percent, accuracy = .1),
                                     &quot;\n&quot;,avg_hours))
                  ,size = 3.8, fontface = &quot;bold&quot;,box.padding = 0.1, position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5)) +
  labs(title = &quot;Average Duration of Waking Time Spent by Activity Type in a Day&quot;, fill = &quot;Activity Type&quot;) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.3, face = &quot;bold&quot;, size = 15,margin = margin(t =10,b = 5)), legend.title = element_text(face = &quot;bold&quot;))+ 
  guides(color = &quot;none&quot;) + # removing just the color legend
  scale_fill_manual(values = my_colors, label = my_labels) + scale_color_manual(values = my_colors)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>Based on the data analysis, it is evident that users spend a
significant portion of their day in sedentary activities, averaging at
13 hours and 10 minutes per day.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="calories-intensity-and-steps-correlation" class="section level3">
<h3>Calories, Intensity and Steps Correlation</h3>
<p>Datasets in use:</p>
<ul>
<li>dailyActivity</li>
<li>minuteStepsNarrow</li>
<li>minuteIntensitiesNarrow</li>
<li>minuteCaloriesNarrow</li>
<li>heartrate_seconds</li>
<li>minuteMETsNarrow</li>
</ul>
<div id="steps" class="section level4">
<h4>Steps</h4>
<p>our next step would be to calculate the mean number of steps per user
using the dailyActivity dataset.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>dailyActivity %&gt;% group_by(Id) %&gt;%
  summarise(user_avg_daily_steps = mean(TotalSteps)) %&gt;% 
  summarise(average_daily_steps = mean (user_avg_daily_steps))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 1  1
##   average_daily_steps
##                 &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1               7922.</code></pre>
<p>The average daily steps of 7922 falls short of the recommended 10,000
steps per day. It would be interesting to see if the overall trend of
daily steps is increasing or not.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>dailyActivity %&gt;% ggplot(aes(x= as.POSIXct(ActivityDate_new), y = TotalSteps)) + 
  geom_jitter() + geom_smooth(method = &quot;lm&quot;) + 
  labs(title = &quot;Daily Steps Among All Users&quot;, x = &quot;Total Steps&quot;, y = &quot;Date&quot;) +
    scale_x_datetime(date_labels = &quot;%Y-%m-%d&quot;, timezone  = &quot;America/Los_Angeles&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>While a linear relationship may provide interesting insights, it
seems that there is no such trend present in the data. Nonetheless,
analyzing the distribution of steps throughout the day may still be
useful in gaining further insights.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>minuteStepsNarrow %&gt;% group_by(hour = format(ActivityMinute_new, format = &quot;%H&quot;)) %&gt;%
  summarise(avg_step = mean(Steps)*60) %&gt;% 
  ggplot(aes(x = hour, y = avg_step)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = &quot;identity&quot;, fill = &quot;#66347F&quot;) +
  labs(title = &quot;Step Count by Hour&quot;, x = &quot;Hour&quot;, y = &quot;Average Steps&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>We can see that the majority of steps are taken between 12:00-20:00,
with a dip between 15:00-16:00.</p>
</div>
<div id="correlation-between-steps-calories-and-intensity" class="section level4">
<h4>Correlation between Steps, Calories, and Intensity</h4>
<p>The first step in our analysis would be to examine the range of
values in each dataset. Once we have assessed the range, we will then
proceed to join the necessary tables.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>unique(minuteIntensitiesNarrow$Intensity) # Four distinct values of intensity: 0,1,2,3</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 0 1 2 3</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>range(minuteCaloriesNarrow$Calories) # 0-19.75</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1]  0.00000 19.74995</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>range(minuteStepsNarrow$Steps) #  Steps ranges 0-220</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1]   0 220</code></pre>
<p>Our next step is to merge the minuteIntensitiesNarrow,
minuteCaloriesNarrow, and minuteStepsNarrow tables.<br> To ensure
computational efficiency, we will take a sample of 100,000 rows out of
the 1,325,580 total rows. This will provide us with a 99% confidence
level and a margin of error of 0.4%.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>cal_int_steps &lt;- inner_join(minuteCaloriesNarrow, minuteIntensitiesNarrow, by = c(&quot;Id&quot;,&quot;ActivityMinute_new&quot;)) %&gt;% 
  inner_join(minuteStepsNarrow,by = c(&quot;Id&quot;,&quot;ActivityMinute_new&quot;))
cal_int_steps &lt;- select(cal_int_steps,c(&quot;Id&quot;,&quot;Calories&quot;,&quot;Intensity&quot;,&quot;Steps&quot;,&quot;ActivityMinute_new&quot;))
sampled_data &lt;- cal_int_steps %&gt;% sample_n(100000) # Using sample of that data</code></pre>
<p>Introducing the correlation analysis between calories and steps.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>sampled_data %&gt;% ggplot(aes(x = Steps, y = Calories)) + geom_jitter() +
  geom_smooth(method = &quot;lm&quot;) +
  geom_text(aes(x=90,y=18, label = paste0(&quot;r = &quot;,round(cor(Steps,Calories),2))),color = &quot;blue&quot;, size = 5) +
  labs(title = &quot;Examining the Steps-Calories Relationship&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>The linear connection between steps and calories burned makes sense,
as physical activity usually leads to higher energy expenditure.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(data = sampled_data,aes(x=Intensity ,y=Calories)) + geom_jitter() +
  geom_smooth(method = &quot;lm&quot;) +
  geom_text(aes(x=1.5,y=18, label = paste0(&quot;r = &quot;,round(cor(Intensity,Calories),2))),color = &quot;blue&quot;, size = 5) +
  labs(title = &quot;Examining the Intensity-Calories Relationship&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>We expect to see a clear separation of calorie burn based on
intensity level and step count. However, we observe some discrepancies
that require further investigation. Specifically, some data points with
higher step count do not necessarily result in a proportional increase
in calorie burn. We can explore why there are no clear distinctions with
steps involved in the next step.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>ggplot(data = sampled_data) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x=Steps,y=Calories,color = factor(Intensity),k = 8,se = FALSE)) + 
  labs(color = &quot;Intensity Level&quot;, title = &quot;Steps and Intensity: A Breakdown of Caloric Burn&quot; ) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(&quot;lightgreen&quot;, &quot;blue&quot;, &quot;orange&quot;, &quot;red&quot;),
                     labels = c(&quot;Low Intensity&quot;,&quot;Light Intensity&quot;,&quot;Moderate Intensity&quot;,&quot;High Intensity&quot;))</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>From the data, we can observe that for a certain level of steps,
light intensity activities burn more calories than moderate intensity
activities.</p>
</div>
<div id="deeper-look-on-intensity" class="section level4">
<h4>Deeper Look on Intensity</h4>
<p>To better understand intensity, we can examine the correlation
between MET and intensity with heart rate data. MET represents the
metabolic equivalent of a task and is a unit of measurement for physical
activities. It indicates the amount of energy expended while sitting
quietly. Physical activities can be rated using METs to indicate their
intensity level.</p>
<pre class="r"><code># heart rate seconds to minutes in order to join with cal_int_steps
heartrate_minutes &lt;- heartrate_seconds %&gt;% 
  group_by(ActivityMinute_new = floor_date(Time_new, unit = &quot;minute&quot;), Id) %&gt;%
  summarize(average_heartrate = mean(Value))

intensityMET &lt;- inner_join(minuteIntensitiesNarrow,minuteMETsNarrow, by = c(&quot;Id&quot;,&quot;ActivityMinute_new&quot;))
intensityMET &lt;- intensityMET %&gt;% select(activity_minute = ActivityMinute_new,id = Id, intensity = Intensity, mets = METs)

intens_met_heartrate &lt;- inner_join(intensityMET,heartrate_minutes, by = c(&quot;id&quot; = &quot;Id&quot;,&quot;activity_minute&quot; = &quot;ActivityMinute_new&quot;))
intens_met_heartrate %&gt;% sample_n(100000) %&gt;% ggplot(aes(x = mets, y=intensity)) + geom_jitter(aes(color = average_heartrate)) +
  geom_smooth(color = &quot;black&quot;,method = &quot;lm&quot;,se = FALSE) +
  geom_text(aes(x=42,y=4.5, label = paste0(&quot;r = &quot;,round(cor(mets,intensity),2))),color = &quot;black&quot;, size = 5) +
  labs(title = &quot;Correlating Intensity with METs Score&quot;,color = &quot;Heart rate&quot;) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = &quot;lightgreen&quot;, high = &quot;red&quot;) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0,3,1)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0,150,20)) +
  theme_bw() +ylab(&quot;Intensity&quot;) + xlab(&quot;MET&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>From the graph, we can observe that there is a minimum amount of MET
required to reach a certain intensity level. For example, level 1 starts
at 21 MET, level 2 starts at 42 MET, and level 3 starts at 60 MET per
minute. However, we can also see that MET is not the only variable that
determines the intensity level, as earlier we saw that the number of
calories burned also plays a role. Additionally, we can observe that
higher intensity levels are associated with higher heart rates.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="sleep" class="section level3">
<h3>Sleep</h3>
<p>Datasets in use:</p>
<ul>
<li>sleepDay</li>
<li>minuteSleep</li>
<li>dailyActivity</li>
</ul>
<p>To begin our analysis, lets start by examining the average amount of
sleep time per user.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>sleepsSumTable &lt;- sleepDay %&gt;% group_by(Id) %&gt;% summarise(avg_user_daily_sleep = mean(TotalMinutesAsleep))
mean(sleepsSumTable$avg_user_daily_sleep)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 377.6475</code></pre>
<p>On average, users sleep for 377 minutes or 6 hours and 17 minutes,
which is below the recommended time. We can further explore the data to
see at what times users tend to sleep.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>minuteSleep %&gt;% ggplot(aes(x= format(date_new, &quot;%H&quot;))) + 
  geom_bar(stat = &quot;count&quot;, width = 0.9, fill = &quot;#001F3F&quot;) +
  labs(title = &quot;Sleep Distribution by Hour&quot;, x = &quot;&quot;, y = &quot;Count&quot;) +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_blank()) + theme_bw()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>The data shows that users on average sleep for 377 minutes or 6
hours and 17 minutes, which is below the recommended sleep time. The
majority of users are observed to be asleep between 23:00 and 07:00,
indicating that the data is reliable. We can now analyze how the sleep
patterns vary across the week.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>sleepInWeek &lt;- sleepDay %&gt;%  mutate(week_day = wday(SleepDay_new, label = TRUE, locale = &quot;en&quot;)) 

sleepInWeek %&gt;% group_by(week_day,Id) %&gt;% summarise(avg_sleep = mean(TotalMinutesAsleep)) %&gt;%
  arrange(week_day) %&gt;% group_by(week_day) %&gt;% summarise(avg_sleep_weekday = mean(avg_sleep)) %&gt;% 
  ggplot(aes(x= week_day, y= avg_sleep_weekday)) +
  geom_bar(stat = &quot;identity&quot;, fill = &quot;#3E54AC&quot;) +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(avg_sleep_weekday)), color = &quot;white&quot;, vjust = 1.5 , size = 6)+
  labs(title = &quot;Minutes of Sleep Throughout the Week&quot;, x = &quot;&quot;, y = &quot;Sleep time (min)&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>Based on the sleep data, we can see that women tend to have more
sleep at the beginning of the week, and there is a significant drop in
sleep time between Wednesday and Thursday. To investigate this further,
we can explore if there is a correlation between light activity and
sleep time. For this, we can use the long-format dailyActivity data,
which includes information on activity type, distance, and time
spent.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>sleepInWeek &lt;- sleepDay %&gt;%  mutate(week_day = wday(SleepDay_new, label = TRUE, locale = &quot;en&quot;)) 
activityDistanceTime &lt;- mutate(activityDistanceTime, week_day = wday(date, label = TRUE, locale = &quot;en&quot;))

sleepVsLight &lt;- inner_join(filter(activityDistanceTime,activity_type == &quot;lightly_active&quot;),
                           sleepInWeek, by = c(&quot;id&quot; = &quot;Id&quot;, &quot;date&quot; = &quot;SleepDay_new&quot;,&quot;week_day&quot;))
sleepVsLight &lt;- select(sleepVsLight,id,average_distance,average_time,week_day, TotalMinutesAsleep)

sleepVsLight %&gt;%  ggplot(aes(x=average_time,y=TotalMinutesAsleep)) + geom_point() +
  labs(title = &quot;Light Activity vs. Sleep Time (in Minutes)&quot;, x = &quot;Light Activity Time&quot;, y = &quot;Sleep Time&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>Based on our analysis, we did not find any significant correlation
between light activity and sleep time. Moving on, lets now examine how
sleep and light activity change throughout the week.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>sleepVsLight %&gt;% group_by(week_day,id) %&gt;% 
  summarise(avg_time = mean(average_time), sleep_time = mean(TotalMinutesAsleep)) %&gt;% 
  group_by(week_day) %&gt;% summarise(avg_time = mean(avg_time), sleep_time = mean(sleep_time)) %&gt;% 
  ggplot(aes(x=week_day, group = 1)) + geom_line(aes(y=sleep_time,  color = &quot;Sleep Time&quot;), size = 1.5) +
  geom_line(aes(y = avg_time,  color = &quot;Light Activity Time&quot;), size = 1.5) +
  labs(color = &quot;&quot;, title = &quot;Weekly Trends in Light Activity and Sleep Durations&quot;) +
  ylab(&quot;Time (min)&quot;) + xlab(&quot;&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>Looking at the graph, we can observe that on Sundays users tend to
sleep the most with the least amount of light activity, while on
Saturdays they have the most amount of light activity but an average
amount of sleep.</p>
<p>After exploring sleep and activity patterns throughout the week, we
will now take a deeper look into sleep stages. We will begin by
examining the typical sleep pattern of users with an average number of
sleep observations.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>colnames(minuteSleep) = to_snake_case(colnames(minuteSleep))

averageObs &lt;- minuteSleep %&gt;% group_by(id, log_id) %&gt;% reframe(sleep_obs = length(value)) %&gt;% 
  arrange(-sleep_obs) %&gt;% slice((n() %/% 2 - 1):(n() %/% 2 + 2)) # %/% is integer division

topMinSleepObserv &lt;- minuteSleep[minuteSleep$id %in% averageObs$id &amp; minuteSleep$log_id %in% averageObs$log_id,]

topMinSleepObserv %&gt;% ggplot() + geom_point(aes(x = as_hms(date_new + hours(12)), y = value)) + # Adding 12h for continuous graph look
  facet_wrap(~log_id) + labs(title = &quot;Snapshots of User Sleep Patterns&quot;) + theme_bw() +
  ylab(&quot;Sleep Value&quot;) + scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(1,3,1)) +xlab(&quot;&quot;) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank())</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>From the initial analysis, it appears that most of the sleep time is
spent in stage 1, with a decreasing amount of time in deeper sleep
stages. Additionally, some users do not have any stage 3 sleep, and
there are variations in the amount of stage 3 sleep cycles among users.
We will now examine the numerical data to gain a more comprehensive
understanding of these observations.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>sleep_labels &lt;- c(&quot;Rapid Eye Movement (3)&quot;,&quot;Non Rapid Eye Movement (2)&quot;, &quot;Light Sleep (1)&quot;)
sleep_values &lt;- c(&quot;#0B2447&quot;, &quot;#19376D&quot;, &quot;#576CBC&quot;)
  
minuteSleep %&gt;% group_by(value) %&gt;% summarise(sleep_percent = n()/ length(minuteSleep$value)) %&gt;% 
  ggplot() + geom_bar(aes(x = &quot;&quot;,y = sleep_percent, fill = rev(factor(value))), stat = &quot;identity&quot;,width = 1) + 
  coord_polar(&quot;y&quot;, start = 0) +
  theme_void() +
  labs(title = &quot;Average Sleep Stage Distribution&quot;, fill = &quot;Sleep Phases&quot; ) + 
  geom_text_repel(aes(x = 1.67, y = sleep_percent, label = scales::percent(sleep_percent, accuracy = .1)) 
            ,size = 4.5, fontface = &quot;bold&quot;, color = rev(sleep_values), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5),box.padding = 0) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 4, size = 18, face = &quot;bold&quot;),
        legend.title = element_text(face = &quot;bold&quot;),
        legend.margin = margin(t = 0, r = 50, b = 10, l = 0)) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = sleep_values, labels = sleep_labels) +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE))</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>According to our initial analysis, only one percent of sleep is in
deep sleep, which is lower than the expected 7-8 minutes per sleep
according to studies. To gain a deeper understanding, we will create a
table that shows the chunks of deep sleep for each user, as well as the
level of sleep, which indicates how many cycles of deep sleep occur
during the sleep period.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>sleep_three &lt;- minuteSleep %&gt;% filter(value == 3) %&gt;% group_by(id) %&gt;% arrange(id,date_new)

current_sleep &lt;- 1
level &lt;- 1
df_row &lt;- 1
deep_sleep_df &lt;- data.frame(id = numeric(), date = POSIXct(),level = numeric()
                    , deep_sleep_length = numeric(),stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

for(i in 2:nrow(sleep_three)){
  time_diff = as.numeric(difftime(sleep_three[i,]$date_new,sleep_three[i-1,]$date_new),units = &quot;mins&quot;)
  if(time_diff &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; time_diff &lt;=1){
    current_sleep &lt;- current_sleep +1
  }else{
    deep_sleep_df[df_row,1] &lt;- sleep_three[i-1,]$id
    deep_sleep_df[df_row,2] &lt;- sleep_three[i-1,]$date_new
    deep_sleep_df[df_row,3] &lt;- level
    deep_sleep_df[df_row,4] &lt;- current_sleep
    
    if(sleep_three[i,]$id == sleep_three[i-1,]$id &amp;&amp;
       as.numeric(difftime(sleep_three[i,]$date_new,sleep_three[i-1,]$date_new),units = &quot;mins&quot;) &lt; 180){
      level &lt;- level + 1
    }else {level &lt;- 1}
    
    current_sleep &lt;- 1
    df_row &lt;- df_row + 1
  }
}
rm(current_sleep, df_row, time_diff)</code></pre>
<pre class="r"><code>deep_sleep_df %&gt;% group_by(id) %&gt;% summarise(avg_deep_per_user = mean(deep_sleep_length)) %&gt;% 
  summarise(average_deep = mean(avg_deep_per_user))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 1  1
##   average_deep
##          &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1         3.18</code></pre>
<p>we found that the average time spent in stage 3 (deep sleep) was only
3 minutes and 10 seconds, which is considerably less than what research
suggests. Now, lets examine how the sleep length observations vary.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>deep_sleep_df %&gt;% ggplot(aes(x = deep_sleep_length)) + geom_bar(stat = &quot;count&quot;)  +
  labs(title = &quot;Deep Sleep Length in One Night: A Close Look&quot;) +
  xlab(&quot;Deep sleep length&quot;) +ylab(&quot;Count&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>Many users have an average deep sleep time of just 1 minute, which
appears to be unusual. To investigate this further, we will examine the
sleep cycles, or levels, of the users.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>deep_sleep_df %&gt;% ggplot(aes(x = level)) + geom_bar(stat = &quot;count&quot;) +
  labs(title = &quot;Deep Sleep Cycles in One Night&quot;) +
  xlab(&quot;Deep sleep cycles&quot;) +ylab(&quot;Count&quot;)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>It appears that most users have only one minute of deep sleep, which
is unusual. When we examine the sleep cycles, we also see that most
users only have one cycle of deep sleep, which is inconsistent with the
typical four to six cycles per night for adults. Furthermore, some users
seem to have more than 20 cycles of sleep, which is not plausible. Given
these findings, we can conclude that the data on deep sleep is
unreliable for further analysis. Therefore, we will not be including our
findings related to sleep stages in the conclusion of our analysis.</p>
<p>Moving on, we have daily data on sleep time and time spent in bed.
Lets take a look at the average time it takes for users to fall asleep,
both overall and throughout the week.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>sleepObserv &lt;- sleepDay %&gt;%
  mutate(time_to_sleep = TotalTimeInBed-TotalMinutesAsleep,
         week_day = wday(SleepDay_new, label = TRUE, locale = &quot;en&quot;))
sleepObserv %&gt;% group_by(Id) %&gt;% 
  summarise(avg_tts_id = mean(time_to_sleep)) %&gt;%
  summarise(average_time_to_sleep = mean(avg_tts_id))</code></pre>
<pre><code>## # A tibble: 1  1
##   average_time_to_sleep
##                   &lt;dbl&gt;
## 1                  42.4</code></pre>
<p>On average, the data set shows that people spend 42 minutes in bed
before they are considered asleep, but it is important to note that this
might include time spent using their phone or engaging in other
activities that do not necessarily reflect the time it takes them to
fall asleep. According to <a href="https://www.sleepfoundation.org/how-sleep-works/sleep-latency">studies</a>,
most adults with healthy sleep patterns typically take 10 to 20 minutes
to fall asleep. Therefore, based on the available data, we can assume
that people spend approximately 22 to 32 minutes engaging in other
activities before falling asleep while in bed. However, without more
information on how the data is determined, it is difficult to determine
where the line between actively trying to fall asleep and simply
spending time in bed while using their phone or engaging in other
activities lies.</p>
<p>Now, lets examine the average time users spend in bed before they
are considered asleep throughout the week.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>sleepObserv %&gt;% group_by(Id,week_day) %&gt;% 
  summarise(avg_tts_id = mean(time_to_sleep)) %&gt;%
  group_by(week_day) %&gt;% 
  summarise(average_time_to_sleep = mean(avg_tts_id)) %&gt;% 
  ggplot(aes(x = week_day,y = average_time_to_sleep)) +geom_col(fill = &quot;#FFD369&quot;, width = 0.8) +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(average_time_to_sleep), vjust = 2, fontface = &quot;bold&quot;), size = 4.5) +
  xlab(&quot;Day in Week&quot;) + ylab(&quot;Average Time in Bed (min)&quot;) +
  labs(title = &quot;Time in Bed before Falling Asleep Throughout the Week&quot;) +theme_classic()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
<br>Based on the data, it seems that Sunday is the day when users take
the longest to fall asleep and spend the most time in bed, while the
time gradually decreases throughout the week. By Thursday, users seem to
fall asleep the fastest. This pattern suggests that people might have
more difficulty falling asleep at the beginning of the week, possibly
due to stress or anxiety associated with the upcoming workweek, and then
become more relaxed as the week progresses.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="conclusion" class="section level2">
<h2>Conclusion</h2>
<p>Our analysis has led to several suggestions that could help Bellabeat
grow and be implemented in the Bellabeat app and marketing strategy.</p>
<div id="encouraging-movement-and-healty-habits" class="section level4">
<h4>Encouraging Movement and Healty Habits</h4>
<ul>
<li>Encourage users to move their bodies by providing insights about
their daily activity routines and abnormal sedentary time, which people
spend 76% of waking time in.</li>
<li>Give users suggestions on burning calories more efficiently, as
light activity can burn more calories than moderate activity with the
same amount of steps per minute.</li>
<li>Help users understand the correlation between steps and calories,
and suggest a number of steps to be taken to reach their calorie goal
within the app.</li>
<li>Promote more physical activity on Sundays by providing personalized
exercise recommendations, hosting fitness challenges, or offering
incentives to increase user motivation.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="monitoring-health" class="section level4">
<h4>Monitoring Health</h4>
<ul>
<li>Monitor heart rate during workouts and warn users if anything seems
abnormal.</li>
<li>Encourage regular weigh-ins to better understand how activity and
habits during the day affect body weight and BMI over time.</li>
<li>Implement more health tips to improve overall health.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="improving-sleep" class="section level4">
<h4>Improving Sleep</h4>
<ul>
<li>Visualize the time it takes for users to fall asleep and provide
personalized insights to help improve their sleeping habits, taking into
account how they spend their time in bed before falling asleep.</li>
<li>Improve users sleeping stages measuring for accurate insights and
tips for better and deeper sleep.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="emphasize-bellabeats-competitive-edge" class="section level4">
<h4>Emphasize Bellabeats Competitive Edge</h4>
<ul>
<li>Highlighting Bellabeat ability to monitor stress, mindfulness,
hydration levels and menstrual cycle as a lot of alternatives like
FitBit do not provide this information and underline those advantages in
the marketing campaign.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
